{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603737"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:42:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:42:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15778"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68029"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8469"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7098"},{"type":"tags","id":"10570"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68029"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe male urethra contains several accessory glands that contribute to urethral secretions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of the segments of the urethra receives secretions from both the bulbourethral and urethral glands.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which is this particular segment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramural urethra","Spongy urethra","Membranous urethra","Prostatic urethra","Prostatic sinus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramural urethra\u003C/strong\u003E is the short segment that passes through the wall of the bladder. The \u003Cstrong\u003Espongy (or penile) urethra\u003C/strong\u003E is the longest portion of the urethra and receives secretions from both the bulbourethral and urethral glands. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emembranous urethra\u003C/strong\u003E is the shortest segment and passes through the external urethral sphincter. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostatic urethra\u003C/strong\u003E receives prostatic secretions through multiple ducts. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostatic sinus\u003C/strong\u003E is a groove on the posterior wall of the prostatic urethra where the ejaculatory ducts open.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The bulbourethral (Cowper\u0027s) glands and urethral (Littr\u00e9\u0027s) glands secrete their contents into the spongy (penile) urethra.","The male urethra has four distinct anatomical segments: preprostatic, prostatic, membranous, and spongy portions."],"references":["Serbanoiu A, Ion RT, Filipoiu F, Tulin A, Enyedi M. Dissection of the Male Urethra Demonstrating Its Topographical Specificity. Cureus. 2024 Aug 1;16(8):e65946. doi: 10.7759/cureus.65946. PMID: 39221353; PMCID: PMC11365459.","Stoddard N, Leslie SW. Histology, Male Urethra. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542238/","Karam I, Moudouni S, Droupy S, Abd-Alsamad I, Uhl JF, Delmas V. The structure and innervation of the male urethra: histological and immunohistochemical studies with three-dimensional reconstruction. J Anat. 2005 Apr;206(4):395-403. doi: 10.1111/j.1469-7580.2005.00402.x. PMID: 15817107; PMCID: PMC1571491.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationsh